\section{Three different "curls" (read this first)}{

It matters which one a given request uses, because \code{curlimpersonate} only
affects some of them:
\itemize{
\item \strong{The \code{curl} R package} (and \code{httr}, \code{httr2}, \code{crul}, and anything else
built on it). This is the usual target. It wraps a copy of the libcurl
\emph{C library}.
\item \strong{R's built-in internet module}, used by \code{\link[=download.file]{download.file()}} with
\code{method = "libcurl"}, \code{\link[=url]{url()}}, and \code{install.packages()}. This links a
\emph{separate} libcurl from the one in the \code{curl} package.
\item \strong{The system \code{curl} command-line program}, used by \code{\link[=download.file]{download.file()}} with
\code{method = "curl"}. A completely separate binary.
}

Throughout the docs, \strong{"the \code{curl} package"} means the R package; \strong{"libcurl"}
means the underlying C library; \strong{"system curl"} means the command-line tool.
}

\section{Two ways to get libcurl-impersonate under the \code{curl} package}{

Which one applies depends on how \emph{your} installed \code{curl} package links
libcurl (check with \code{\link[=impersonate_linkage]{impersonate_linkage()}}):
\itemize{
\item \strong{Preload (no rebuild)} — works when the \code{curl} package links libcurl
\emph{dynamically} (typical on Linux). Set a loader environment variable
(\code{LD_PRELOAD} on Linux) \emph{before R starts} so the existing \code{curl.so} picks
up libcurl-impersonate. See \code{\link[=impersonate_env]{impersonate_env()}}.
\item \strong{Rebuild} — required when the \code{curl} package links libcurl \emph{statically}
(the CRAN macOS binary does this). \code{\link[=build_impersonate_curl]{build_impersonate_curl()}} compiles the
\code{curl} package from source against libcurl-impersonate into a private
library; \code{\link[=activate]{activate()}} puts it first on the search path. Nothing in your
main library is modified.
}

Either way, \strong{no \code{.Rprofile} is edited for you.} The functions report
exactly what to run or which variables to set; you decide where to put them
(interactively, in \code{.Rprofile}, in \code{.Renviron}, or in your shell).
}

\section{Choosing a profile and how headers behave}{

Once libcurl-impersonate is in use it does nothing until you select a target
with the \code{CURL_IMPERSONATE} environment variable (via \code{\link[=impersonate_set]{impersonate_set()}}).
\code{CURL_IMPERSONATE_HEADERS} controls whether the library \emph{also} installs the
browser's default request headers and their ordering. See \code{\link[=impersonate_set]{impersonate_set()}}
for how that interacts with headers you set yourself through \code{httr2},
\code{httr}, or \code{curl}.
}

\section{download.file() and friends}{

Because they use different libcurls (see above):
\itemize{
\item \code{download.file(method = "libcurl")}, \code{url()} — use R's internet module, a
\emph{separate} libcurl. The \strong{rebuild} mechanism does \strong{not} affect these.
The \strong{preload} mechanism \emph{does} (it is process-wide), on platforms where
that module links libcurl dynamically.
\item \code{download.file(method = "curl")} — shells out to system curl; affected only
if a curl-impersonate wrapper is first on \code{PATH}.
\item \code{curl::curl_download()}, \code{httr}/\code{httr2} downloads — use the \code{curl} package,
so both mechanisms affect them.
}

Always confirm your specific call path with \code{\link[=impersonate_check]{impersonate_check()}}.
